WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.125 --> 00:00:03.444
Meconium Aspiration Syndrome, or MAS,
occurs

2
00:00:03.444 --> 00:00:08.105
when a newborn inhales meconium-stained
amniotic fluid before or during delivery.

3
00:00:08.225 --> 00:00:11.784
That meconium doesn't just sit there, it
creates a cascade

4
00:00:11.784 --> 00:00:16.064
of problems that can rapidly compromise
both oxygenation and ventilation.

5
00:00:16.465 --> 00:00:18.584
Here's the core concept you need to lock
in.

6
00:00:19.165 --> 00:00:21.665
MAS is a mixed pathophysiology disease.

7
00:00:22.084 --> 00:00:24.444
You're dealing with airway obstruction,
inflammation,

8
00:00:25.145 --> 00:00:29.844
surfactant inactivation, and pulmonary
hypertension all at the same time.

9
00:00:30.485 --> 00:00:31.504
First, the obstruction.

10
00:00:32.325 --> 00:00:35.985
Meconium can partially block airways,
creating a ball valve effect.

11
00:00:36.604 --> 00:00:38.665
Air gets in, but can't fully get out.

12
00:00:39.005 --> 00:00:41.505
This leads to air trapping and
hyperinflation.

13
00:00:41.724 --> 00:00:45.564
But in other areas, complete obstruction
can cause atelectasis,

14
00:00:45.764 --> 00:00:49.485
so now you have uneven ventilation across
the lungs.

15
00:00:50.444 --> 00:00:52.924
Second, inflammation and surfactant
dysfunction.

16
00:00:53.625 --> 00:00:55.104
Meconium is chemically irritating.

17
00:00:55.505 --> 00:00:59.485
It damages the alveoli and inactivates
surfactant, making the lungs

18
00:00:59.485 --> 00:01:01.444
stiff and harder to ventilate.

19
00:01:02.084 --> 00:01:05.404
That increases the work of breathing and
worsens oxygenation.

20
00:01:06.504 --> 00:01:09.385
Third, and critically, persistent
pulmonary hypertension

21
00:01:09.385 --> 00:01:11.364
of the newborn, or PPHN.

22
00:01:12.105 --> 00:01:16.684
Hypoxia causes pulmonary vasoconstriction,
which increases pulmonary pressures and leads

23
00:01:16.684 --> 00:01:18.144
to right-to-left shunting.

24
00:01:18.444 --> 00:01:22.425
That means blood is bypassing the lungs
entirely, making oxygen

25
00:01:22.425 --> 00:01:23.764
therapy less effective.

26
00:01:24.745 --> 00:01:28.404
Clinically, these babies present with
respiratory distress shortly after birth.

27
00:01:28.944 --> 00:01:31.665
You'll see tachypnea, grunting, nasal
flaring,

28
00:01:32.144 --> 00:01:34.285
retractions, and often coarse breath
sounds.

29
00:01:35.144 --> 00:01:38.464
Oxygen levels may be difficult to
maintain, even with increasing

30
00:01:38.464 --> 00:01:38.944
support.

31
00:01:39.345 --> 00:01:43.305
From a diagnostic standpoint, chest x-ray
often shows patchy

32
00:01:43.305 --> 00:01:45.544
infiltrates with areas of hyperinflation.

33
00:01:46.364 --> 00:01:49.785
ABGs may show hypoxemia and, if fatigue
sets in,

34
00:01:50.245 --> 00:01:51.364
rising carbon dioxide.

35
00:01:51.605 --> 00:01:53.444
So what's your role as the RT?

36
00:01:54.004 --> 00:01:55.944
First, support oxygenation.

37
00:01:56.644 --> 00:01:59.525
Start with supplemental oxygen, but be
ready to escalate quickly.

38
00:02:00.285 --> 00:02:02.004
Second, optimize ventilation.

39
00:02:02.644 --> 00:02:06.665
These patients may require CPAP or
mechanical ventilation, but you

40
00:02:06.665 --> 00:02:07.464
must be careful.

41
00:02:07.964 --> 00:02:11.065
Because of air trapping, you want to allow
adequate expiratory

42
00:02:11.065 --> 00:02:13.664
time to avoid worsening hyperinflation.

43
00:02:14.904 --> 00:02:18.884
Third, monitor closely for persistent
pulmonary hypertension of the newborn,

44
00:02:19.164 --> 00:02:20.024
or PPHN.

45
00:02:20.544 --> 00:02:24.744
If oxygenation isn't improving as
expected, think shunting.

46
00:02:25.384 --> 00:02:28.804
These patients may need advanced therapies
like inhaled nitric oxide.

47
00:02:28.964 --> 00:02:32.264
And finally, recognize deterioration
early.

48
00:02:32.945 --> 00:02:36.145
Worsening oxygenation, rising carbon
dioxide, or

49
00:02:36.145 --> 00:02:40.044
increasing work of breathing are all red
flags that require escalation.

50
00:02:40.705 --> 00:02:42.664
For board exams, remember this.

51
00:02:43.005 --> 00:02:44.524
MAS is not just obstruction.

52
00:02:45.065 --> 00:02:49.205
It's obstruction plus inflammation plus
pulmonary hypertension.

53
00:02:49.505 --> 00:02:53.005
And your management decisions must address
all three.

54
00:02:53.404 --> 00:02:56.304
As you go through this lesson, focus on
connecting the

55
00:02:56.304 --> 00:02:58.764
pathophysiology to your clinical
decisions.

56
00:02:59.164 --> 00:03:02.464
That's what will make you a strong,
confident respiratory therapist.

